# **2\. Mechanical Ground Support Equipment**

## **2.1 Objective**

The integration and testing of a 6U CubeSat require specialised mechanical ground support equipment (MGSE) to **secure and handle the satellite** during assembly, transport, and environmental tests. Such MGSE can include Integration and Testing jigs, to be used to support the satellite during assembly and testing of onboard components, carrying cases for external transport of the CubeSat, jigs for vibration testing, and any other ground equipment required for integration, testing and transport of the CubeSat.

Commercially available jigs are typically designed to accommodate smaller CubeSats in the 1U to 3U range. However, since Galassia-5 is a 6U CubeSat, an off-the-shelf jig is not suitable. 

As the person responsible for MGSE on Galassia-5, I am tasked with developing a Modular Assembly and Test Jig (“Integration Jig”) that can hold the CubeSat in both vertical and horizontal orientations, to allow for the integration and testing of the satellite.

## **2.2 Design Specifications (jig)**

The Integration Jig should fulfil the following requirements:

* **Dimensions/Orientation:** Must accommodate a 6U CubeSat (roughly 10×20×30 cm) in all 3 orientations. Support surfaces should match the CubeSat’s outer dimensions or attach to its frame.  
*   **Load Capacity:**  Carry the satellite’s full weight (approx 9kg) plus safety margin (target ≥2× satellite mass). Resist handling and vibration loads without significant deflection.  
* **Modularity:** The jig should be modular to support different orientations.  
*  **ESD Safe:**.Parts that contact the CubeSat must be ESD-safe to prevent the buildup and sudden discharge of static electricity, which can damage sensitive onboard electronics. Using conductive or static-dissipative materials ensures that any charge is safely dissipated rather than abruptly released.  
* **Low Outgassing:** Materials must be space‑qualified for low outgassing (e.g. aluminum alloys, stainless steel, space‑grade plastics) since the jig may be placed in the thermal vacuum chamber and thus exposed to vacuum conditions. Outgassing occurs when materials release trapped/volatile gases when in vacuum, which can then condense onto critical surfaces such as optics and sensors, which could degrade instrument performance.   
* **Lightweight:** Minimize mass to ease handling.  
* **Ease of transport:** The jig must be portable within the cleanroom. Handles or lifting points should be integrated.  
*  **User ergonomics**: The design must allow technicians clear access for wiring and integration. Adequate **clearance to underside** is needed for access to the bottom of the satellite.  
* **Ease of manufacture:** Use readily available materials and processes (CNC machining, laser cutting, extrusion) to keep costs low. Aim for a total parts cost significantly below existing MGSE kits. Simple design 

## **2.3 Concept Generation**

### 2.3.1 Concept Design for Jig

Market research conducted during Concept Generation shows that the 6U CubeSat market appears to be underserved, with the availability of specialised jigs and test fixtures for this size remaining limited. For example, there appears to be only one commercially listed rotating jig (by EnduroSat) explicitly referenced for 6U form‑factors. 

**Rotating Jig**  
![Fine-tuned fixturing][image1] ![Image of 6U CubeSat integration rotating jig photo][image2]https://www.canadianmetalworking.com/canadianfabricatingandwelding/article/welding/fine-tuned-fixturing  
[https://www.endurosat.com/products/rotary-jig/](https://www.endurosat.com/products/rotary-jig/)

Rotating jigs consist of a circular base plate mounted on a turntable (either horizontal or vertical), with fixtures mounted to hold the CubeSat. The major advantage of such designs allow technicians to rotate the CubeSat easily to access all faces during assembly and integration. However, such designs are also technically more complex to manufacture and also requires locking mechanisms to lock the rotation in place during works.

**Base plate with Stands/Support Brackets**  
![A black rectangular object with metal partsAI-generated content may be incorrect.][image3]  
[https://www.cubesatshop.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ISIS-Integration-Support-Jigs-Brochure-v1.pdf](https://www.cubesatshop.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ISIS-Integration-Support-Jigs-Brochure-v1.pdf)

These stands can be easily removed/changed, potentially allowing different configurations (vertical/horizontal) and the entire assembly can be easily transported within the cleanroom. Although the base plate itself does not rotate on a turntable, the overall lightweight nature of the CubeSat and jig assembly still allows technicians to shift the entire assembly as needed to access different parts during integration and testing.

**Decision Matrix**

| :---: | :---: | :---: |
| Ease of access to different parts of CubeSat | \+ | 0 or \- |
| Modularity (change of configuration) | \- | \+ |
| Ease of transport | \- | \+ |

| Decision |  | ✔ |

### 2.3.2 Material Selection

As mentioned under Design Specifications, the jig must support the CubeSat’s full weight and have low outgassing properties. Aluminium 6061, commonly available in NUS, is sufficiently strong and has low outgassing, making it suitable as base plate material.

However, parts in contact with the CubeSat (such as the stands/fixtures) need to **additionally** be ESD safe and ideally made of plastic to prevent damage to the CubeSat’s frame. 

3D Printing ESD plastics in-house is not feasible without significant investment in creating an isolated printing environment to ensure thorough filtration and ventilation of volatile organic compounds and particulates produced by carbon black or carbon nanotubes, in compliance with OSHA requirements. Hence, the chosen plastic should be easily machinable.

Another key consideration is the maximum temperature required for the thermal vacuum (TVAC) cycling test. If the peak temperature is limited to 80 °C, more common ESD plastics such as polycarbonate (PC-ESD) could be used. However, for higher temperatures (e.g., 100 °C), more thermally stable options like polyphenylene sulfide (PPS-ESD) should be considered to ensure safety and performance.

 Some plastics were evaluated and presented in the decision matrix below:

| Material | ESD POM, e.g. Semitron ESd 225 (Acetal) | ESD Polycarbonate | Conductive UHMW-PE | ESD grade PEI / PEEK |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Price | 4/5 | 3/5 | 3/5 | 2/5 |
| Lightweight/ Machinability | 5/5 | 4/5 | 5/5 | 3/5 |
| Resistance to Outgassing | 4/5 | 3/5 | 3/5 | 5/5 |
| ESD Safety | 4/5 | 4/5 | 3/5 | 5/5 |
| Availability | 4/5 | 3/5 | 3/5 | 2/5 |
| Total Score | 21/25 | 17/25 | 17/25 | 17/25 |

CNC-machined aluminium with an ESD powder coating presents the most practical solution, provided that the coating does not substantially increase costs compared to procuring ESD-grade material directly for CNC machining. Since the CubeSat rail can be hard anodised, they would still be acceptable even without an ESD coating, although plastic alternatives would inherently avoid surface scratching. 

## **2.4 Detailed Design**

Several designs were developed to optimise the jig for supporting the CubeSat.

### 2.4.1 First Iteration 

The design consists of an Aluminum base plate of dimensions 400 x 260 x 100 mm.  
![][image4]  
Fig. Base Plate V1. The Red, Magenta and Green lines denotes the CubeSat position for each orientation.

Two types of support brackets/stands are mounted to the base plate from underneath using countersunk M5 screws, to accommodate different orientations of the CubeSat: 

* Corner towers (Vertical Orientation) – vertical POM posts that interfaces with the CubeSat rails at all 4 corners of the CubeSat, holding the CubeSat in the vertical position   
* Rail Blocks – low-profile POM blocks that interfaces with the CubeSat rails. The Rail Blocks are spaced sufficiently far apart for the CubeSat rails at either edge of the CubeSat to fit snugly into the gap, holding the CubeSat in place.

On the advice of the industry partner, the stands were raised to allow a 50 mm clearance beneath the CubeSat to provide access to bottom components.  
![][image5]![][image6]

Fig. Corner Tower \+ Rail Block

To validate the concept, a 3D-printed prototype was fabricated. Because the available printer (a Bambu Labs A1 Mini) did not have a sufficiently large build plate to accommodate the entire base plate in one piece, the base plate had to be downsized, split into four separate parts and put together using M3 screws. The hole positions for mounting the stands were not shifted.

A fit test was conducted using a 3D-printed mock-up of Galassia-5, and it was verified that the CubeSat fit properly in both the horizontal and vertical orientations onto the support brackets on the jig.

![][image7]  
Fig. Assembled Iteration 1 Jig with Galassia-5 3D-printed mockup (here shown in Vertical Orientation)

One observation during simulation was that the total mass of the jig would be close to 4kg, which was deemed somewhat heavy for the application. Additionally, during installation there was difficulty aligning the screw holes on the stand with those on the base plate.

### 2.4.2 Second Iteration 

To reduce the weight of the Jig assembly, material was removed from the base plate to by cutting out holes. This brought the final mass of the aluminium base plate down to 1.8 kg, a reduction of 35% compared to the original design.

| Overall Mass of Jig (empty) | First Iteration | Second Iteration |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Horizontal Configuration | 3.7 kg | 2.6 kg |
| Vertical Configuration | 3.3 kg | 2.2 kg |

Finite Element Analysis (FEA) was conducted to evaluate the structural performance of the modified base plate, confirming that it could withstand loads well beyond those expected for its intended application of supporting a 9 kg CubeSat, despite the reduction in material.

![][image8]  
Fig. FEA (both ends fixed, total load of 180N (twice the intended load))

To facilitate precise alignment during assembly, 2 mm deep recesses matching the dimensions of the support blocks were machined into the base plate. This ensured that the screw holes would align accurately when the support blocks were placed into position. In accordance with Design for Manufacturing principles, T-bone fillets were incorporated into the recesses to provide suitable toolpaths for the milling cutter to ensure machinability.

## **2.5 Future Work**

### 2.5.1 Possible Improvements to the Jig 

* For ease of transport, handles can be procured and installed onto the jig. Noting that handles may obstruct access to the CubeSat from certain angles, the handles should be easily removable with minimal and easily accessible screws.  
* A concern was raised that the end blocks may obstruct Solar Panel deployment during testing (Solar Panels Deployment will be tested in the horizontal orientation to simulate a low-gravity environment and reduce stresses on the hinges). Pending confirmation of the solar panel hinge design, the end block design may have to be modified to ensure that the Solar Panel hinges are not obstructed.  
* The current rail block design covers the entire longitudinal edge of the CubeSat, which prevents access to the underside of the CubeSat from the longitudinal edge. The rail block can be modified to hold only the corners of the CubeSat, however any stresses to the structure has to be studied.  
* The support blocks are currently installed using screws fitted from below the assembly, which is inconvenient. A future iteration should explore having the screws fitted from above to allow for easier change of configuration.
